{{redirect|RYB}}
{{refimprove|date=September 2017}}
[[File:Color mixture.svg|thumb|right|Mixture of RYB primary colors]] [[File:Pigment Colours - Classification.jpg|thumb|Classification of pigment colors]]
'''RYB''' (an abbreviation of [[red]]–[[yellow]]–[[blue]]) is a historical set of [[Color|colors]] used in [[subtractive color]] mixing and is one commonly used set of [[primary color]]s. It is primarily used in art and design education, particularly [[painting]].
RYB predates modern scientific [[color theory]], which has determined that [[CMYK color model|cyan, magenta, and yellow]] are the best set of three colorants to combine, for the widest range of high-chroma colors.<ref> {{cite book | title = Color and Light: A Guide for the Realist Painter | author = James Gurney | publisher = Andrews McMeel Publishing | year = 2010 | isbn = 978-0-7407-9771-2 | page = 75 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=MvddjqkQy9UC&pg=PA75 }}</ref>
==Color wheel== {{double image|right|BYR color wheel.svg|150|Color_star-en (tertiary names).svg|150|RYB [[color wheel]]|RYB color star}}
RYB (red–yellow–blue) make up the primary color triad in a standard artist's [[color wheel]]. The [[secondary colors]] [[purple]]–[[orange (colour)|orange]]–[[green]] (sometimes called [[violet (color)|violet]]–orange–green) make up another triad. Triads are formed by three equidistant colors on a particular color wheel. Other common color wheels represent the [[RGB color model|light model (RGB)]] and the [[CMYK color model|print model (CMYK)]].
==History== [[File:Franciscus Aguilonius color scheme.png|thumb|The 1613 RYB color scheme of Franciscus Aguilonius (Francisci Agvilonii), with primaries yellow (flavus), red (rubeus), and blue (caeruleus) arranged between white (albus) and black (niger), with orange (aureus), green (viridis), and purple (purpureus) as combinations of two primaries.]] [[File:Traité_de_la_peinture,_1708.png|thumb|Claude Boutet's 1708 color circle uses the same arrangement of primary and secondary color names as modern RYB color circles.]] [[File:Le Blon three-color printing.png|thumb|Le Blon's 1725 description of mixing red, yellow, and blue paints or printing inks]]
The first known instance of the RYB triad can be found in the work of [[Franciscus Aguilonius]] (1567–1617), although he did not arrange the colors in a wheel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Franciscus Aguilonius |work=Colorsystem: <!--different spellings in original-->Colour order systems in art and science |url=http://www.colorsystem.com/?page_id=629&lang=en |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213041900/http://www.colorsystem.com/?page_id=629&lang=en|archivedate=2014-02-13}}</ref>
In his experiments with light, [[Isaac Newton]] recognized that colors could be created by mixing color primaries. In his ''[[Opticks]]'', Newton published a color wheel to show the geometric relationship between these primaries. This chart was later confused and understood to apply to pigments as well,<ref name=hprint1>{{cite web |last=MacEvoy |first=Bruce |date=April 19, 2009 |title=handprint : color wheels |url=http://handprint.com/HP/WCL/color13.html |accessdate=2009-06-30}}</ref> though Newton was also unaware of the differences between additive and subtractive color mixing.<ref name=hprint2>{{cite web |last=MacEvoy |first=Bruce |date=April 19, 2009 |title=handprint : do "primary" colors exist? |url=http://handprint.com/HP/WCL/color6.html#confusions |accessdate=2009-06-30}}</ref>
The RYB model was used for printing, by [[Jacob Christoph Le Blon]], as early as 1725.{{fact|date=May 2017}}
In the 18th century, the RYB primary colors became the foundation of theories of color vision, as the fundamental sensory qualities that are blended in the perception of all physical colors and equally in the physical mixture of pigments or dyes. These theories were enhanced by 18th-century investigations of a variety of purely psychological color effects, in particular the contrast between [[complementary colors|"complementary"]] or opposing hues that are produced by color afterimages and in the contrasting shadows in colored light. These ideas and many personal color observations were summarized in two founding documents in color theory: the ''[[Theory of Colors]]'' (1810) by the German poet and government minister [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe]], and ''The Law of Simultaneous Color Contrast'' (1839) by the French industrial chemist [[Michel-Eugène Chevreul]].{{fact|date=May 2017}}
Painters have long used more than three RYB primary colors in their palettes, and at one point considered red, yellow, blue and [[green]] to be the ''four'' primaries.<ref>For instance Leonardo da Vinci wrote of these four simple colors in his notebook circa 1500. See Rolf Kuenhi. “Development of the Idea of Simple Colors in the 16th and Early 17th Centuries”. ''Color Research and Application''. Volume 32, Number 2, April 2007.</ref> Red, yellow, blue and green are still widely considered the four [[psychological primary color]]s,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Stroebel |first1=Leslie D. |last2=Current |first2=Ira B. |year=2000 |title=Basic Photographic Materials and Processes |publisher=Focal Press |isbn=0-240-80345-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BRYa6Qpsw48C&pg=PP1&dq=Basic+Photographic+Materials+and+Processes}}</ref> though red, yellow and blue are sometimes listed as the ''three'' psychological primaries,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ross |first1=MS Sharon |last2=Kinkead |first2=Elise |year=2004 |title=Decorative Painting & Faux Finishes |publisher=Creative Homeowner |isbn=1-58011-179-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DPJUWRydR9kC&dq=red+yellow+blue+paint-mixing++subtractive}}</ref> with black and white occasionally added as a fourth and fifth.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Swirnoff |first1=Lois |year=2003 |title=Dimensional Color |publisher=W. W. Norton & Company |isbn=0-393-73102-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sG5MqtZuFF0C&dq=%22psychological+primaries%22+blue+-green}}</ref>
The cyan, magenta, and yellow primary colors associated with [[CMYK color model|CMYK]] printing are sometimes known as "process blue", "process red"{{citation needed|date=January 2013}} and "process yellow".{{fact|date=May 2017}}
[[File:Chromatography 1841 Field.png|thumb|An RYB color chart from [[George Field (chemist)|George Field]]'s 1841 ''Chromatography; or, A treatise on colours and pigments: and of their powers in painting'' showing a red close to magenta and a blue close to cyan, as is typical in printing.]]
