{{selfref|To cite this reference on Wikipedia, use {{tl|ThePlantList}}.}} {{Infobox website | name = ''The Plant List'' | logo = ThePlantList.png | logo_size = 260px | screenshot = | caption = ''The Plant List'' | url = {{URL|http://www.theplantlist.org/}} | commercial = | type = [[Encyclopedia]] | language = [[English language|English]] | registration = | owner = | launch date = December 2010 | current status = version 1.1 September 2013 | author = [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]] and [[Missouri Botanical Garden]] | alexa = [http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/theplantlist.org 138,478] as of 20140119 }}
'''The Plant List''' is a list of [[botanical name]]s of species of plants created by the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]] and the [[Missouri Botanical Garden]] and launched in 2010.<ref name="discovery news">{{cite web | url=http://news.discovery.com/earth/plant-database-library-101229.html | title=World's Largest Plants Database Assembled | publisher=[[Discovery News|discovery.com]] | date=2010}}</ref> It was intended to be a comprehensive record of all known names of plant species over time.
There is a complementary project called the [[International Plant Names Index]], in which Kew is also involved. The IPNI aims to provide details of publication and does not aim to determine which are accepted species names. Newly published names are automatically added from IPNI to the [[World Checklist of Selected Plant Families]], a database which underlies the Plant List.
==Findings== The Plant List has 1,064,035 scientific [[plant]] names of [[species]] rank.<ref name="The Plant List">{{cite web | url=http://www.theplantlist.org/ | title=Summary Statistics | work=The Plant List | accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref> 350,699 are accepted species names, belonging to 642 plant [[Family (biology)|families]] and 17,020 plant [[genus|genera]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/cp/science/i81521.html|title=US, British scientists drew up the comprehensive list of world's known land plants|publisher=CBC }} {{Dead link|date=September 2011|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> The Plant List accepts approximately 350,699 unique species, with 470,624 [[Synonym (taxonomy)|synonym]]s for those species, which suggests that many species have been referred to under more than one name. {{As of|2014}}, The Plant List has determined that another 243,000 names are 'unresolved', meaning that botanists have so far been unable to determine whether they are a separate species or a duplication of the 350,699 unique species.
==Public attention== When The Plant List was launched in 2010 (the [[International Year of Biodiversity]]), it attracted media attention for its comprehensive approach. [[Fox News]] highlighted the number of synonyms encountered, suggesting that this reflected a "surprising lack" of biodiversity on earth."<ref name="Fox News">{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/scitech/2010/12/30/worlds-plant-life-far-diverse-previously-thought/#ixzz19t9BPqzQ|title=World's Plant Life Far Less Diverse Than Previously Thought|publisher=Fox News | date=30 December 2010}}</ref> The Plant List also attracted attention for building on the work of [[English people|English]] [[natural history|naturalist]] [[Charles Darwin]], who in the 1880s started a plant list called the [[Index Kewensis]] (IK). Kew has added an average of 6,000 species every year since the IK was first published with 400,000 names of species.<ref name="Fox News"/> However, the IK (which by 1913 avoided making taxonomic judgement in its citations) is currently run as part of the IPNI rather than the Plant List.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ipni.org/ik_blurb.html | title = About the Index Kewensis | accessdate = | author = | authorlink = | coauthors = | date = | year = 2004 | month = | work = | publisher = [[International Plant Names Index]] | quote = }}</ref>
